How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high vis-à-vis Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really like to start the fight.
It may sound absurd, as well as here we have three mobile networks and cover well above 100 %.
On the other hand, the operators of the mobile telophony like to boast that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, it also often emphasizes the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTU) , Pavel Dvořák, who in the past has expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network no longer probably has many possibilities. (Of course, it would be difficult to find other frequencies now).
But there's still another possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a significant fall in prices, to which traditional operators should have reacted.
At the same time before the entry of sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile into the market, there were similar voices like us in Britain.
But it has been shown that the place for such operators is there and that they can really succeed.
In the end, we must not go too far for examples.
In February this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In only half a year, this operator managed to conquer more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta to which the Czech Republic belongs, among other things, U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete group-best.
In order to be able to function effectively, it is enough for them to be much less customer than for a traditional operator.
They do not lead behind, i.e. relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually come at low cost, they offer calls and SMS at little price, which is often in balance with the offer of the most limited services
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers SMS that cost as little as half as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be quite a good move, too, to bet on a small group-bestage.
This operator aims to say specifically about men.
“The real men choose Mobilking operator that they like and can trust,” says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can affirm a similar concept as in Poland.
The press spokesperson for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický doubts this: -The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition from the point of view of services it is relatively saturated -
In the Czech Republic, there are no possibilities, mobile operators say
But it seems almost certain that if there ever will be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations do not have many expectations.
The ignition of Mobilking will take place rather in the other countries of our area, - he said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman for the Penta financial group.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the present operators in the Czech Republic are not quite in favour of this.
Rather, they try to do everything because they do not create any competing potential.
For some time it has not hidden its interest for the start of a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefonika O2 in the business customer field.
We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And it's better before.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all the blind operators of the mobile network.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them, says the spokesman for the Pavel Kaidl Group.
So maybe better times will come.
The unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will probably have it by the end of the year.
But for now around his creation there is an impenetrable wall of silence.
\"At the moment we do not believe that in the Czech market there is room for the creation of a full virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us, - mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň of the press section of Telephonnika O2.
The specificities of the Czech market also apply to other operators.
T-Mobil Martina Kemrová’s press spokesman adds in a rare agreement with the declaration O2: “For now we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue to build”
And he adds: “In the T-Mobile network, a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At the moment we have already had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered at the horizon -
Vodafone focuses its attention rather than reaching its own requests under the 3G licence.
Add Miroslav Čepický : -We are open to negotiations of potential virtual operators, and this is especially in the context of the sharing of expenditure and infrastructure.
Let us consider this, from the point of view of the customers, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet -
The competent authorities - with the complicit operators
The attitude of mobile operators can easily be understood, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profit.
Why, then, facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The discomforts around the creation U:fon testify that when operators tend to something they can row from the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure against ČTU in the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to the public access information from ČTU websites.
But now just U:fon serves as a topic for which not to accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová observed: \"The environment of mobile telephone market competition has been little further enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would put on him and above all on his high-pretense services -
However, from the attitude of mobile operators it is quite surprising that the Czech regulatory bodies are completely disinterested.
It is not just the attitude of the ČTU that unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
That belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, has taken its typical position in relation to all the problems.
The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between mobile operator and virtual operator has been completed.
No such contracts have been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been quite interesting for traditional operators, - said Kristián Chalupa, from the section for external relations ÚOHS, in response to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators may not surprise us.
On the other hand, the office which must defend the interests of consumers and above all to deal with the fact that no one takes advantage of its position on the market is more than a delicate deal.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: “Outside where virtual operators commonly operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephone services”
But, of course, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of UIOHS.
