The same as the same price of gasoline for all gas stations is certainly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
The section found no evidence of anti-competitive behaviour on this issue and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it has no greater responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The necessary tools for the opening up of the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecom regulator, - said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points .
Of course there is the analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTú, according to which telecommunications is from the point of view of economic competition the only market.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator is always necessary the agreement of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has - in the end of the accounts logically - the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not admit this argument, for UOHS it should be a minimum alert that three mobile operators do so strangely similar.
At the same time, complaints from stakeholders (including the mentioned GTS Novera company) show that during negotiations with all operators encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to ČTU in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which ÚOHS is kept out of the whole matter.
We have already found this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of ČTU's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved telecommunications law was updated, despite the fact that many experts were expecting improvement in the situation from this point of view.
This fact the representatives of UOHS must know more than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
You can do it when no one looks.
While we are not aware of this, there is still the functioning of such pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are even some in the Czech mobile networks.
These companies publish their mobile phone services price lists but are only partially public.
These are usually companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only pre-determined people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company towards the operator appears as a classic company customer, which orders a large amount of SIM card.
