The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a pre-sale.
\"If the cases you are talking about, which we will be interested in, could be a breach of contractual conditions, and could result in the conclusion of cooperation with that company,\" answered Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would reach the ears of the actors responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, there can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies they bring a non-indifferent profit and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems:-The law allows similar speculations, however only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered on their behalf, so they cannot have full of it as the regular customers of mobile operators -
But this should be a little strange at the ČTU.
There is also another question for UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes in the face of such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
