The Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr FrancineDecary, had every reason to rejoice, for Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective providers in the world.
And above all, it has regained the public's confidence, seriously shaken by the scandal of the infected blood between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a tragedy and the protests of the population, in February 1994 the Government of Canada conducted a public investigation, conducted by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of a similar disaster.
While Judge Krever was slow to draw up a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of designing a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gelineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Québec started its activities, just 38% of people declared that they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to our continued efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research in the following years, we have regained public confidence - it explains before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec's population had already trusted in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that trust is something extremely fragile.
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were many cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of the softness of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, telling the president that she has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of the foundation.
“And we didn’t know at all if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
There is therefore one of the main recommendations of Krever and Gélinau's reports, according to which when there are doubts and there could be a serious disease, in this case the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob which manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980 was refused.
Now, for some years now, it has been shown that this disease is undoubtedly transmitted through infected blood.
This episode has thus shown us that it has made sense to apply the precautionary principle -
In 1999 a much more efficient technique appeared on the market for the identification of HIV: Nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow the blood of donors to recognize the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, that is from the moment the person contracted the disease to that in which the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could have been reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and therefore not being able to identify them is thus greatly diminished.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one out of 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion is found.
I think we can feel calm today when we receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover the health, says the head of the Hema-Québec management.
Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than a year ago the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by an insect.
We need to be constantly vigilant - Dr. Décary continues before stressing that in addition to having secure resources, Hema-Québec must also provide enough for it.
The need is increasing as the population is ageing.
