Smart machine mimics calabron flight
What could be the best way to develop anti-collition technologies if you do not imitate the sensors of the obstacles in nature?
For example, bees.
In the amazing project presented to the CETAEC in Japan, the calabron gave the initial strategic trigger to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-lock systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotized mini-car with bees properties, with the ultimate aim of creating a system able to scan all collisions.
Flying the bees form a personal oval space that really resembles our protective shield - explained to the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technology and research and development.
Important is the role of the ape view, capable of a view of 300 degrees in each direction.
Engineers have drawn to the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the ape view.
The BR23C detects the obstacles up to two meters away within a 180 degree radius, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor that immediately transforms it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the ape, changes direction immediately by turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, unlike the current system, is carried out in a completely instinctive manner.
“If it wasn’t so, the robot car wouldn’t be able to react quickly to avoid collisions,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the auto robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the harmful layer and more internal than the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in an eye beater.
But unlike bees the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available for bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by batteries to lithium polymers, lighter and with high energy density, which means that their duration is greater than those of lithium ions.
According to Andoh it is important the instantaneity of the intelligent reaction, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store them.
This robot must process some inputs in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to memorize and react with intuitive logic based on previous manoeuvring data, so it uses only a memory of a few tens of Kb.
No need for a memory of gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, for Nissan, within 10 years can be installed on standard vehicles.
Further application possibilities can be represented by unification with GPS satellite navigation system that avoids obstacles on the road leads to destination.
