What matters most, we need to sensitize consumers and make this information public.
We also need to review existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, in order to ensure that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology.
Brussels asked the independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise from them.
‘Scientists — concludes the EU’s executive — confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and interested parties what measures could be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and related equipment.’
At present, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical equipment to 100 dB, but concerns about hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such noise sources are growing.
It is possible to limit these damage by using solutions such as reduced noise levels and duration of exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical equipment if they listen at high volume (more than 89 decibels) music for only 5 hours a week exceed the current limits on maximum permitted noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music under these conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing ability after a period of 5 years.
This would involve 5-10% of the users of these devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 million and 10 million people in the EU.
