Good-bye old cinema Paradise, cities erase historical halls
The historical cinemas close in favor of the Multiplexes.
\"A city without cinematographic rooms is a blind town, it's like a face without eyes\"
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore pictures effectively what is happening in the large Italian urban centres but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the outskirts of the large multisales and the consequent death for the consumption of monosales in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that appear to us inescapable and incontrovertible but also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are often historical places and loaded with memory, it is as if there was less of a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of road and many emotions\", notes the director of New cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago was worth to Tornatore the Oscar Prize and the Grand Prix of the Jury of Cannes, and who told the poetry of a province hall and nostalgia for a way to live the lost cinema perhaps forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of the exercents, speak clearly: in the last five years they have closed the 316 films of traditional type, and to pay the major discount are mainly the rooms in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the areas most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinema monosala lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And in a demonstration that the first person responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multisala cinemas: 195 extra screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
\"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally\" observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, - it is useful that new structures are built but it would be necessary to ensure the survival of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all of his visitors are willing to move into multiplex.
Not to mention, then, the lack of funding for the fund in favour of the depositors: the state's prior debt is about EUR 10 million.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the government does not respect existing laws.
In order to support the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be needed\".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, concerned about the closures, decided to run to the shores with the signing of a protocol between Comune and Anec, the first such in Italy, to protect and promote monosala cinemas both in the historical center and in the periphery.
Among the rules envisaged are tax facilitation measures in favour of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: the spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for the stop and some parking.
“It’s an initiative that I like” notes Giuseppe Tornatore and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is true, however, that in order to counter the overpowering of multiplex, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do \"New Paradise cinema\" to which I had been thinking for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale now closed, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, not to see the posters nestled by the dust I turn to the other side\".
